        <!-- Payment methods -->
        <section id="payment" class="content-section">
          <h2>How to Pay USCIS Filing Fees</h2>
          <div class="payment-methods">
            <div class="pm-item pm-yes">
              <span class="pm-icon">✅</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Check or money order</strong>
                <p>Payable to "U.S. Department of Homeland Security." Most reliable for mailed petitions. Write your name and address on the back.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="pm-item pm-yes">
              <span class="pm-icon">✅</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Online payment (credit/debit card)</strong>
                <p>Available when filing through the USCIS online portal at my.uscis.gov. Visa, MasterCard, American Express, and Discover accepted.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="pm-item pm-yes">
              <span class="pm-icon">✅</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Bank draft (ACH)</strong>
                <p>U.S. bank account holders can pay by ACH bank transfer through the USCIS online portal.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="pm-item pm-no">
              <span class="pm-icon">🚫</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Cash — never accepted</strong>
                <p>USCIS does not accept cash payments under any circumstances. Cash sent in an envelope will result in rejection.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Fee waiver info -->
        <section id="fee-waiver" class="content-section">
          <h2>Fee Waivers — Who Qualifies?</h2>
          <p>USCIS fee waivers exist for some immigration forms, but they are <strong>not available for the K-1 process</strong>:</p>

          <div class="waiver-table-wrap">
            <table class="fee-table">
              <thead>
                <tr><th>Form</th><th>Fee Waiver Available?</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>I-129F (K-1 petition)</td>
                  <td class="fw-no">❌ No</td>
                  <td>No waiver available</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>MRV consular fee ($265)</td>
                  <td class="fw-no">❌ No</td>
                  <td>Paid to State Dept., not USCIS</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>I-485 (Adjustment of Status)</td>
                  <td class="fw-maybe">⚠️ Sometimes</td>
                  <td>Form I-912 required; must show inability to pay and meet criteria</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>I-765 / I-131 (EAD/AP)</td>
                  <td class="fw-maybe">⚠️ Sometimes</td>
                  <td>Waivable when filed separately; included in I-485 bundle</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>I-751 (Remove Conditions)</td>
                  <td class="fw-maybe">⚠️ Sometimes</td>
                  <td>Available for certain low-income applicants with Form I-912</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <section id="faq" class="content-section">
          <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
          <div class="faq-list">
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>How much does a K-1 visa cost in 2026?</summary>
              <p>The K-1 visa alone costs $940 in government fees ($675 for I-129F + $265 MRV fee). But the full path from K-1 petition to a green card costs approximately $3,680 in government fees. With medical exams, translations, and optional attorney or filing service fees, most couples spend $5,000–$10,000+ total over the 2–3 year process.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What is the I-129F filing fee?</summary>
              <p>$675 as of 2026, paid by the U.S. citizen petitioner to USCIS. Non-refundable. Pay by check or money order (payable to "U.S. Department of Homeland Security") when mailing, or by credit card/ACH when filing online through my.uscis.gov.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>How much does Adjustment of Status cost after K-1?</summary>
              <p>$1,440 for Form I-485 (which includes the EAD work permit and Advance Parole travel document when filed concurrently). Plus approximately $200–$500 for the I-693 medical exam by a civil surgeon inside the U.S. Total AOS government fees: ~$1,740 before out-of-pocket costs.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Are K-1 visa fees refundable?</summary>
              <p>No. All USCIS filing fees are non-refundable, including the I-129F ($675), I-485 ($1,440), and I-751 ($750). The MRV consular fee ($265) is also non-refundable. If your petition is denied, you must refile from scratch and pay again.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Is K-1 cheaper than CR-1?</summary>
              <p>No — K-1 is more expensive. The full K-1 path costs ~$3,680 in government fees vs. ~$2,220 for CR-1. You also pay for two medical exams on K-1 vs. one on CR-1. The K-1's advantage is faster U.S. entry, not lower cost. If you're already married or willing to marry abroad first, CR-1 saves $1,400–$2,000+.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Can I get a fee waiver for the K-1 visa?</summary>
              <p>No. USCIS fee waivers are not available for Form I-129F or the MRV consular fee. A fee waiver (Form I-912) may be available for the I-485 Adjustment of Status application for qualifying low-income applicants, but not for the initial K-1 petition stages.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </section>

